1. What are boolean operators in Java?
-->Boolean operators are used to perform operations on boolean values (true / false).
    👉 Main boolean (logical) operators:
    && → Logical AND
    || → Logical OR
    ! → Logical NOT
    📌 Example:
    boolean a = true;
    boolean b = false;
    System.out.println(a && b); // false
    System.out.println(a || b); // true
    System.out.println(!a);     // false


2. What is the default value of a boolean variable?
-->✔ Depends on where it is declared:
    Instance variable (class level) → false
    Static variable → false
    Local variable (inside method) → ❌ No default value (must initialize)
    
    📌 Example:
    
    class Test {
        boolean flag; // default = false
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            System.out.println(t.flag); // false
        }
    }


3. Difference between Boolean (wrapper class) and boolean (primitive type)?
-->
| Feature | `boolean`         | `Boolean`                                  |
| ------- | ----------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| Type    | Primitive         | Wrapper class                              |
| Value   | true/false        | Object (can be `true`, `false`, or `null`) |
| Memory  | Less              | More                                       |
| Usage   | Simple conditions | Collections, APIs, null handling           |




4. Can boolean be converted to int directly?
-->❌ No, Java does NOT allow direct conversion
    👉 You cannot do:
    int x = true; // ❌ Compile-time error
    ✔ You must convert manually:
    boolean flag = true;
    int x = flag ? 1 : 0;
    System.out.println(x); // 1
